@node OVERVIEW "AutoConnect Overview"
Overview

One of the few things I like about those wintel boxes is
the semi-automatic network connection when you attempt to
use the tcp/ip stack. These arexx scripts provide similar
capabilities when used as a wrapper for your internet
applications.

You must customize a script for each of your tcp/ip apps
for this process to work. This is just identifing the full
path to the appliction. The scripts call a common routine
at startup to make sure Miami is launched and online. At
shutdown, a similar call checks to see if this was the last
application running, and if so, offers you a chance to
shutdown Miami.

The ideal (for me anyway) way to use these scripts is in
conjuction with a toolmanager style dock, but scripts can
be used in many ways. For example, with one click, I start
YAM on its way. No remembering to launch Miami first, no
checking to see if maimi is online or not, just one click
and I'm in my e-mail account. Same for browser, ftp, etc.
Its so convienient, I now take it forgranted.

@endnode

@node SYSREQ "System Requirements"
REQUIREMENTS
 - arexx
 - Miami and appropriate internet applications
 - ability to copy and edit a few files
 - ability to install those files in your REXX: directory

@endnode

@node INSTALL "Installation"

Installing

Copy the following files to REXX: (usually S: or sys:s)
 ac_miami_off.rexx
 ac_miami_on.rexx

These two files comprise the brains of the operation.

For each internet application, choose a suitable starting
script and modify it as described below. There are two
basic script shells, one for MUI apps which can only have 
one copy running, such as YAM, the other for apps which can
be started multiple times, such as IBrowse or AmFTP.

Use @{" ac_single.rexx " link SINGLE} for single instance apps
and @{" ac_multi.rexx " link MULTI}  for multiple instance apps.

@endnode

@node SINGLE "Single Instance Applications"

Single Instance Applications

ac_single.rexx is preset for YAM, and looks like this:
------------------------------------------------------------------------
/* laucher for MUI internet apps that support only a single occurance */
ncommand = 'yam:yam'
nport = 'YAM'
options results
address command 'rx ac_miami_on.rexx'
if(rc>0) then do
 exit
end
x=show('Ports',nport)
if (x=1) then do
 address value nport
 'SHOW'
 setclip('ac_cnt', getclip('ac_cnt') - 1)
 exit
end
address command ncommand
address command 'rx ac_miami_off.rexx'
------------------------------------------------------------------------

To change this script for another application, change the line

	ncommand = 'yam:yam'

by substituting the full path to your applications for the yam:yam
portion.

Also change the line

	nport = 'YAM'

to indicate the REXX PORT name of the application.

Please note that this script works with MUI apps only. If the
application is not a MUI program, you will need to find some
other solution. The @{" multi version " link MULTI} does not have this limitation.
The only real distinction here, is that if invoked a second
time, the single script just brings forward the GUI for the
program instead of launching it again.

Name the modified version appropriately, and copy it to REXX: 
or your directory of choice for rexx scripts.

@endnode

@node MULTI "Multiple Instance Applications"

Multiple Instance Application

ac_multi.rexx looks like this:
------------------------------------------------------------------------
/* laucher for internet apps which support multiple invocations */
ncommand = 'inettools:myapp'
address command 'rx ac_miami_on.rexx'
if(rc>0) then do
 exit
end
address command ncommand
address command 'rx ac_miami_off.rexx'
------------------------------------------------------------------------

To change this script for another application, change the line

	ncommand = 'inettools:myapp'

by substituting the full path to your applications for the 
inettools:myapp portion.

Name the modified version appropriately, and copy it to REXX: 
or your directory of choice for rexx scripts.

@endnode

@node NOTES "Usage"

Using the Scripts

To use these scripts, simply start the 'rx' command with the
name of the script. The supplied icons do this, for example.
The one thing to watch out for is stack size. Programs which
don't get enough stack space tend to create unpredictable
crashes. In addition, MUI apps tend to need more stack than
comparable programs. This is why I recommend running 'rx' as
opposed to just submitting the script to the rexx port directly,
as it gives a place for you to specify the stack.

For example, using toolmanager, use the cli type for the exec
object, and specify 'rx scriptname.rexx' as the command instead
of specifiying it as a rexx type. This is based on experience,
not hard fact, so if you know what you're doing, just do it.

Some testers have observed 'crashes' as a result of using this.
The stack problem has been identified as the culprit every time.
I use it in the manner described above with toolmanager, with
stack set to 12000 (for most MUI apps) in the exec objects, and
it works like a charm.

@endnode

